@DATABASE Rainbow V1.00
$VER: PureBasic - Rainbow library V1.00 (24.08.2000) © Fantaisie Software
@NODE MAIN "Rainbow"

  @{b}PureBasic - Rainbow V1.00@{ub}

    The Amiga has a little chip called 'Copper' which is used
    to synchronize the whole display. This chip is amazing and
    can be 'programmed'. With the help of this chip, it's possible
    to create stunning visual tricks and the most common is
    probably the rainbow one. It just displays a nice rainbow in the
    background of your screen. Yes, but it uses only one color and
    can add upto 256 gradients. It's a way to display more than
    256 colours on a single screen. This library uses the AGA copper
    to produce easily 16M colours vertical rainbows. It's of course
    fully multitasking and OS compliant. The CPU overhead is near to
    zero as it's done by the hardware.

  @{b}Commands summary:@{ub}

    @{" CreateRainbow " LINK CreateRainbow}
    @{" FreeRainbow   " LINK FreeRainbow}
    @{" HideRainbow   " LINK HideRainbow}
    @{" InitRainbow   " LINK InitRainbow}
    @{" RainbowColor  " LINK RainbowColor}
    @{" RainbowEnd    " LINK RainbowEnd}
    @{" ShowRainbow   " LINK ShowRainbow}

    @{" Rainbow Demo  " LINK PureBasic:Examples/Sources/Rainbow.pb/Main}
@ENDNODE



@Node CreateRainbow

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  @{b}Result@{ub}.l = CreateRainbow(#@{b}Rainbow@{ub}.l,@{b}NumOfCol@{ub}.l)

    @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
  Create a new rainbow object, ready for use.

  This function don't care if the object is already
  initialized, make sure it's free.

  @{b}Rainbow@{ub}
  The rainbow to create.

  @{b}NumOfCol@{ub}
  The maximum possible colors in the rainbow,
  one on each line of the screen.

  @{b}Result@{ub}
  If TRUE the rainbow object has been succesfully
  created, otherwise it's FALSE.
@EndNode


@Node FreeRainbow

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  FreeRainbow(#@{b}Rainbow@{ub}.l)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  Use this statement to swap the rainbow object
  out of memory.

  @{b}Rainbow@{ub}
  The rainbow to free.
@EndNode


@Node HideRainbow

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  HideRainbow(#@{b}Rainbow@{ub}.l)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  Removes the rainbow from the screen.

  @{b}Rainbow@{ub}
  The rainbow to hide.
@EndNode


@Node InitRainbow

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  @{b}Result@{ub}.l = InitRainbow(@{b}Rainbows@{ub}.l)

    @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
  This function is the initroutine and must always be
  called before any other rainbow functions.

  @{b}Rainbows@{ub}
  The maximum wanted rainbow objects.

  @{b}Result@{ub}
  If this is TRUE then all is fine, else none of the
  other rainbow functions could be called.
@EndNode


@Node RainbowColor

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  RainbowColor(#@{b}Rainbow@{ub}.l,@{b}YPosition@{ub}.w,@{b}Red@{ub}.b,@{b}Green@{ub}.b,@{b}Blue@{ub}.b)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  To have some color, on a specific line, in the
  rainbow then call this statement.

  @{b}Rainbow@{ub}
  The rainbow to add a color on.

  @{b}YPosition@{ub}
  The position on screen where this color
  is displayed.

  @{b}Red@{ub}
  The value which represents the red color.

  @{b}Green@{ub}
  The value which represents the green color.

  @{b}Blue@{ub}
  The value which represents the blue color.
@EndNode


@Node RainbowEnd

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  RainbowEnd(#@{b}Rainbow@{ub}.l)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  When no more colors are about to be put on the rainbow
  then call this statement to have it ended.

  @{b}Rainbow@{ub}
  The rainbow to end.
@EndNode


@Node ShowRainbow

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  ShowRainbow(#@{b}Rainbow@{ub}.l,@{b}ScreenID@{ub}.l)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  Call this statement to put the rainbow on the
  desired screen.

  @{b}Rainbow@{ub}
  The rainbow to put on the screen.

  @{b}ScreenID@{ub}
  The rainbow will be displayed on this screen until
  HideRainbow() is called.
@EndNode

